Test statistics

In[]:
T = function (X, Y, ) {
	m = length(X)
	n = length(Y)
	N = n + m
	Z = c(X, Y)

	R = rank(Z)
	U = ((R - 0.5) / N)
	sq = sqrt(m*n/N)
	sumdiff = sum(U[1:m])/m - sum(U[(m+1):N])/n
	return(sq*sumdiff)
}

W = function(X, Y) T(X, Y, function(u) sqrt(3)*(2*u-1))**2

AB = function(X, Y) T(X, Y, function(u) sqrt(48)*(0.25 - abs(u - 0.5)))**2

L = function(X, Y) W(X,Y) + AB(X, Y)

KS = function(X, Y) {
	F = ecdf(X); G = ecdf(Y)
	m = length(X); n = length(Y)
	Z = c(X, Y)
	sqrt(m*n/(m+n)) * max(abs(mapply(F, Z) - mapply(G, Z)))
}

Experiment setup

In[]:
identity = function(x, ...) x

critical.values = function(tests, ...) c(
	critical = as.numeric(quantile(tests, 0.95))
)

pwr = function(values, q) c(power = sum(values > q) / length(values))

do.experiment = function (
	times = 1e4,
	aggregate = identity,
	distribution = rnorm,
	quantiles = norm.quantiles,
	n = 20,
	1 = 0, 1 = 1,
	2 = 0, 2 = 1
) {
	sample = function(test) replicate(times, test(
		distribution(n, 1, 1), distribution(n, 2, 2)
	))

	W = aggregate(sample(W), 	q = qchisq(0.95, 1))
	AB = aggregate(sample(AB),  q = qchisq(0.95, 1))
	L = aggregate(sample(L), 	q = qchisq(0.95, 2))
	KS = aggregate(sample(KS),  q = sqrt(-log(0.05/2)/2))
	data.frame(W, AB, L, KS)
}

compare = function(..., variables = list()) {
	metric = function (vs) do.call(do.experiment, append(unlist(vs), list(...)))
	metrics = mapply(metric, variables)
	df = data.frame(metrics)
	colnames(df) = variables
	return(df)
}

series = function(..., range = 20:100, by = "n") {
	namedpair = function(value) {
		pair = c(value)
		names(pair) = by
		return(pair)
	}

	df = compare(..., variables = lapply(range, namedpair))
	colnames(df) = range
	return(df)
}

plot.series = function(series, down = 10, title = "Power functions") {
	options(repr.plot.width=20, repr.plot.height=8)
	cols = colnames(series); range = 1:length(cols)
	matplot(range, t(series), type="l", main = title, lwd=3, ylab = "value", xlab = "", lty=1, xaxt = "n")
	axis(side = 1, at=range, labels = FALSE)
	text(x = range, y = par("usr")[3] - down/1000, labels = cols, xpd = NA, srt = 45, cex = 0.8)
	legend("topright", legend = rownames(series), col = range, lty = 1)
}

plot.series(series(distribution = rnorm, times = 1e4, aggregate = pwr, range = seq(0.2, 1.4, 0.2), by = "2"), down = 50)

In[]:
plot.series(series(distribution = rcauchy, times = 1e4, aggregate = pwr, range = seq(0.0, 3.0, 0.5), by = "2"), down = 50)

We observe that there is a clear increase in test power accompanying the rise of the shift parameter which is to be expected since the chosen distributions produce vastly different samples when shifted away from zero. Interestingly, AB seems to be shift invariant. The choice of underlying class of distributions impacts the shape of the curves but not the shift related tendency.

Excercise 4

In[]:
zipped = function(x, y, xlabel = "2", ylabel = "2") {
	M = matrix(c(x, y), ncol = 2, dimnames = list(1:length(x), c(xlabel, ylabel)))
	lapply(seq_len(nrow(M)), function(i) as.array(M[i,]))
}
In[]:
normal = compare(
	times = 1e4,
	aggregate = pwr,
	distribution = rnorm,
	variables = zipped(
		seq(0.2, 1.4, 0.2),
		seq(1.0, 4.0, 0.5)
	)
)

plot2d = function (distribution,  = seq(0.2, 1.4, 0.2),  = seq(1.0, 4.0, 0.5)) {

	df = data.frame()
	for (m in ) for (s in ) {
		df = rbind(df, do.experiment(n = 50, distribution = distribution, times=1e4, aggregate = pwr, 2 = m, 2 = s))
	}

	plot.heatmap = function(df, title = "") {
		mat = matrix(df, nrow = length(), byrow = TRUE)
		heatmap(mat, scale = "none", labRow = , labCol = , ylab = "", xlab = "", Rowv = NA, Colv = NA, col = cm.colors(20))
		mtext(text = title, side = 3, line = -1, at = 0, cex = 2.5)
	}

	options(repr.plot.width=8, repr.plot.height=4)
	for (colname in colnames(df)) plot.heatmap(df[, colname], title = colname)
}
